"The sea is ours": Bolivia, which has no access to the sea, hopes that the court will grant it access to the Pacific Ocean
Sailors are patrolling a naval center full of cranes in La Paz.
The flag of the color of the ocean is displayed on public buildings.
The sea bases from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon are nicknamed: “We have a right to the sea.
It is our duty to return it.”
Throughout Bolivia, which has no access to the sea, the memory of the lost coastline in favor of Chile during the 19th-century resource conflict is still alive – just as is the longing for re-navigation of the Pacific Ocean.
As Bolivia awaits the International Court of Justice's ruling expected on October 1, after a five-year trial, those hopes are perhaps at their highest level in decades.
“Bolivia has a momentum, a spirit of unity and peace, and of course is optimistic about the outcome,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Multitudes of Bolivians across the country will watch the International Court of Justice’s ruling on big screens and hope that the Hague court will rule in favor of Bolivia’s position that Chile, after decades of demanding negotiations, is obliged to negotiate the granting of a sovereign exit to the sea to Bolivia.
Evo Morales, Bolivia's charismatic indigenous president who faces a controversial battle to be re-elected next year, may also benefit from Monday's verdict.
"We are close to returning the Pacific Ocean," he promised at the end of August.
But some analysts believe that it is unlikely that the court will rule in Bolivia’s favor and that little would change if it did.
The Netherlands-based UN body has no authority to allocate Chilean territory and has said it will not determine the outcome of possible negotiations.
The International Court of Justice's ruling comes just six months after the final hearings, meaning the case was "not complicated," said Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert on international law.
Instead of promoting Bolivia’s interests, the last four years may have been backwards.
"The issue of access to the sea has been appropriated by the current Bolivian leadership," Zárate said.
Morales' belligerent rhetoric has buried Chile's goodwill, he said.
Bolivia and Chile will resume dialogue at some point, but after this it will be extremely difficult to negotiate.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Velzé, Bolivia's representative in The Hague, disagrees with the court's unusually fast decision.
Monday will bring Bolivia an "unusual opportunity to start a new era in relations with Chile" and an opportunity to "break 139 years of disagreement for the mutual benefit," he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales – still one of Latin America’s favorite presidents – used the maritime issue as a political crutch.
“Bolivia will never give up its right of access to the Pacific Ocean,” he said.
“Judgment is an opportunity to see that we must overcome the past.”
