John Edward: The Language Skills Citizens of the World Need
Scottish independent schools have a tradition of academic excellence, which continued in 2018 with another package of outstanding exam scores, with individual and collective success in sport, art, music and other community activities giving it extra weight.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best level of service to their students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare students for further education and higher education, the career they want and make them citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement the mentioned school curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a favorite and desired subject of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you talk to a man in a language he understands, it goes to his head.
If you speak to him in his mother tongue, it goes to his heart.”
This statement is a powerful reminder that we cannot use English alone if we want to build trust and relationships with people from other countries.
The latest results of the final exams this year show that the highest scores in languages were achieved by participants of independent schools.
A total of 68% of students who studied foreign languages received excellent grades.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools show that 72% of students received an excellent grade for Mandarin, while 72% of students learning German, 69% of students learning French and 63% of students learning Spanish also received the highest possible grade.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as a key skill that children and young people will certainly need in the future.
Today, languages as electives are considered as important as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curriculum of independent schools as well as elsewhere.
A survey conducted by the UK Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 found that 17% of employers are unable to fill jobs due to a shortage of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly becoming an imperative for preparing young people for careers.
With more and more jobs demanding language skills, these skills are crucial in a globalised world.
Regardless of the choice of career, people who have learned to speak a foreign language in the future will experience the benefits of such long-term skills.
A person who speaks multiple languages can communicate directly with strangers, and this gives him an advantage over the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in 2013, 75 % of respondents in the UK do not know a foreign language well enough to communicate in it, and French is the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage of respondents, namely 15 %.
Therefore, investing in language learning is very important for today’s children.
If children learn more languages, especially the languages of developing countries, they will have more opportunities to find good jobs.
In Scotland, each school offers a variety of languages.
Some schools will include classical, modern languages in their curriculum, while others will opt for the languages that are considered to be most important in the UK in 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of your child’s interests, independent schools will always have a diverse selection, as well as teaching staff who are experts in the field.
Scottish independent schools provide children with an environment in which learners can prepare and equip themselves with the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future holds for us.
One cannot ignore the fact that in today’s global business time, language skills are very important for the future of every country, so this must also be reflected in education.
Thus, the knowledge of modern languages should really be seen as “international communication skills”.
Independent schools will continue to offer language choice, diversity and excellence to young Scots.
It's going to be fair.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Independent Schools Council.
