North Korea says there is "no chance" of unilateral disarmament without trust
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that further sanctions increase distrust of the United States and there is no chance that North Korea will unilaterally disarm and give up its nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the UN General Assembly that North Korea last year took "significant goodwill measures" such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling a nuclear test site and deciding to halt the development of nuclear technology and weapons.
"However, we have not received a satisfactory response from the United States," he added.
"If we don't trust the United States, we don't trust our national security. Under such circumstances, there's no way we're going to be the first to unilaterally disarm."
While Ri reiterated North Korea’s well-known complaints about Washington’s resistance to a “gradual” approach to denuclearization that would gradually lift sanctions on North Korea, his statement is significant because he did not reject unilateral denuclearization as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first meeting in the history of the incumbent U.S. and North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work to “denuclearize the Korean peninsula,” while Trump guaranteed North Korea’s security.
North Korea wants to formally end the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has conditioned Pyongyang to give up its nuclear weapons beforehand.
Washington has also ignored calls to cut tough international sanctions on North Korea.
“The United States insists on prior denuclearization and increases pressure through sanctions to force its goal, and even opposes the ‘declaration of the end of the war,’” Ri added.
“The perception that sanctions can bring us to our knees is just a misconception by people who know nothing about us.
The main problem is that the continuation of sanctions increases mistrust."
Ri did not mention whether there were plans for a second meeting between Kim and Trump, which the US president spoke about earlier this week at the United Nations.
But he said Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in had held as many as three meetings in the past five months, adding: "If denuclearization had been sought by South Korea and not the United States, denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have come to such a standstill."
Regardless, the tone of Mr. Rio’s speech differed greatly from last year when he spoke before the UN General Assembly and said targeting the continental U.S. with missiles was inevitable after the evil President Trump called Kim a “man rocket” on a suicide mission.
Trump, who last year threatened "total destruction" of North Korea, praised Kim at the United Nations this year for his courage to disarm, but added that there was still a lot of work to be done and that sanctions must remain in place until North Korea denuclearizes.
Trump said on Wednesday that there was no timetable for denuclearization, adding: "It doesn't matter if it lasts two years, three years or five months."
China and Russia have expressed the view that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday: “The implementation of Security Council sanctions must continue strictly until complete, final and verified denuclearization is achieved.”
The Security Council unanimously imposed sanctions on North Korea in 2006 in an attempt to halt funding for its nuclear and ballistic missile programs in Pyongyang.
Pompeo met with Ri at the UN General Assembly and then said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second meeting.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last visit did not go well.
He left Pyongyang in July and said progress had been made, but was dubbed by North Korea after hours of "gangster demands."
North Korea has agreed to meet with Moon this month to dismantle the missile site and nuclear complex, which will happen if the United States takes "appropriate measures".
He added that Kim had told him that the “appropriate measures” related to the security guarantees Trump promised in Singapore and certain steps toward stabilizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course to learn how to get a good night’s rest
A new course at Harvard University has enabled all students to get a good night’s sleep in an attempt to combat an increasingly widespread culture of caffeine-filled learning and sleepless nights.
The academician found that students at the world’s best university often have no idea about the basics of taking care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a sleep science professor at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, has devised a course he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He came up with the idea of the course after giving a speech on the effect of sleep deprivation on learning.
At the end of the lecture, a girl came up to me and said, "Why did I only learn this now, in my final year of college?"
She said no one told her how important sleep was, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, held for the first time this year, explains to students how good sleep habits help in academic and sports success and improve health in general.
Professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the University’s health service, Paul Barreira, said the university decided to introduce the course after students were observed to be severely sleep deprived during the week.
The one-hour course consists of a series of interactive assignments.
One of these tasks involves a picture of a student dormitory where students have to click on cups of coffee, curtains, sneakers and books to find out what the effects of caffeine and light are, how lack of sleep affects success, and how important a sleep routine is.
During the lectures, students also learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
After that, a campus map with interactive icons is displayed that encourages students to think about their daily routine.
"We know that the behavior of students will not change immediately.
But we think they have a right to know, just as you have a right to know how cigarettes affect health," added Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride in night-long learning before exams still exists, says the professor and adds that modern technology and increasing pressure on students prove that lack of sleep is a growing problem.
The professor says that the secret weapon of students against stress, exhaustion and anxiety should be a good and quality sleep. Sleep also helps in the fight against weight gain, because lack of sleep affects the brain, puts it in a state of starvation and causes constant hunger.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old chemistry and biology student from California, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending his first year of Harvard.
He says the course opened his eyes and inspired him to extend the course to the entire campus.
As a next step, he plans to ask all postgraduates to complete a similar study course before joining a competing institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students turn on the alarm during sleep, as well as during waking up. They must be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by the screens of electronic devices, as well as LED lights that can disrupt the circadian rhythm and cause sleep problems.
