Almanac: The Inventor of the Geiger Counter
And now a page from our Almanac on Sunday Morning: September 30, 1882, 136 years and a few days ago...the day of the birth of the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, and from this invention later developed a device known as the Geiger counter.
The mainstay of science since that time, the Geiger counter has also become a mainstay of pop culture, for example in the 1950 film "Bells of Colorado" in which the seemingly incredible scientists Roy Rogers and Dale Evans played the main roles:
Man: "What the hell is that?"
Rogers: "It's a Geiger counter, and it's used to detect radioactive minerals, like uranium.
When you put these headphones on, you can actually hear the atoms reacting to the radioactivity in the minerals."
Evans: "Look at that, it's true!"
Hans Geiger died in 1945, just days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name lives on.
