New data on red tide: Concentrations are decreasing in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission (FWC) shows a general reduction in red tide concentrations in parts of Tampa Bay.
According to the FWC, conditions of heterogeneous algae flowering are reported in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, indicating a decrease in concentrations.
The red tide stretches about 130 miles along the coast from the northern part of Pinellas County to the southern part of Lee County.
The flowering areas can be found about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer places than last week.
The red tide was also spotted in Pasco County.
In the past week, mean concentrations have been recorded in the district of Pinellas or in the associated off-shore area, low to high concentrations in the offshore area of Hillsborough County, common to high concentrations in the district of Manatee, common to high concentrations in the district of Sarasota or in the associated off-shore area, common to high concentrations in the district of Charlotte, common to medium concentrations in the district of Sarasota or in the district of Charlotte.
Cases of respiratory irritation continue to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
Respiratory irritation has not been reported in northwest Florida over the past week.
